## Fahoum Fahoum

**Fahoum Fahoum** (Arabic: فاهوم فاهوم, Hebrew: פאהום פאהום) is a Palestinian citizen of Israel and peace activist from Haifa. He has promoted peace‑building initiatives through sport, earning two congressional awards, one presented by **[Congresswoman Shelley Berkley](/Shelley_Berkley)** in 2001. Fahoum represented the national junior tennis team in European and world championships and later competed in collegiate tennis. &#91;1&#93; &#91;2&#93;

### Education  

He graduated from high school in 2009 at the **[Hebrew Reali School](/Hebrew_Reali_School)** in **[Haifa](/Haifa)**, majoring in economics and psychology, &#91;3&#93; and earned a Bachelor of Arts in Public Relations from **[Quinnipiac University](/Quinnipiac_University)** in **[Hamden, CT](/Hamden,_CT)** in May 2014. &#91;4&#93; In 2016 he received a Master’s degree in Negotiation and Conflict Resolution from **[Columbia University](/Columbia_University)**. His research examined the use of sport as a conduit for improving inter‑group relations. He later published his findings and personal testimony in the **[Wall Street Journal](/The_Wall_Street_Journal)**. &#91;5&#93;

### Athletic career  

Growing up in Haifa, Fahoum trained at the **[Israel Tennis Center](/Israel_Tennis_Centers)**. At age twelve he attended the **[Wingate Institute](/Wingate_Institute)** south of **[Netanya](/Netanya)**. He competed nationally and internationally, representing his country at the **[Junior Davis Cup](/Junior_Davis_Cup_and_Junior_Billie_Jean_King_Cup)**, **[Petits As](/Petits_As)**, and the **[Orange Bowl](/Junior_Orange_Bowl_(tennis))** tournaments. From 2009 to 2012 he played collegiate tennis at **[Old Dominion University](/Old_Dominion_University)** before transferring to **[Quinnipiac University](/Quinnipiac_University)** in 2012.

